04859nam a22006255i 9780226816517DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20222022ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2021041556  a9780226816517  a(DE-B1597)625625  a(OCoLC)1306057321  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aPR408.S845bD36 2022 4aPR408.S845bD36 2022 7aLIT0000002bisacsh04a820.9/3548223/eng/202205051 aDaniel, Drew, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aJoy of the Worm :bSuicide and Pleasure in Early Modern English Literature /cDrew Daniel. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (288 p.) :b3 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThinking Literature00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction • Renaissance Self- Finishing -- tChapter 1 • Failed Seriousness in the Old Arcadia and Gallathea -- tChapter 2 • Slapstick and Synapothanumenon in Antony and Cleopatra -- tChapter 3 • Trolling Decorum in Hamlet and Timon of Athens 94 -- tChapter 4 • The Open Window in Biathanatos -- tInterlude • Inventing Suicide in Religio Medici -- tChapter 5 • A Cartoon about Suicide Prevention in Paradise Lost -- tChapter 6 • Smiling at Daggers in Cato, a Tragedy -- tEpilogue -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aConsulting an extensive archive of early modern literature, Joy of the Worm asserts that voluntary death in literature is not always a matter of tragedy. In this study, Drew Daniel identifies a surprisingly common aesthetic attitude that he calls “joy of the worm,” after Cleopatra’s embrace of the deadly asp in Shakespeare’s play—a pattern where voluntary death is imagined as an occasion for humor, mirth, ecstatic pleasure, even joy and celebration. Daniel draws both a historical and a conceptual distinction between “self-killing” and “suicide.” Standard intellectual histories of suicide in the early modern period have understandably emphasized attitudes of abhorrence, scorn, and severity toward voluntary death. Daniel reads an archive of literary scenes and passages, dating from 1534 to 1713, that complicate this picture. In their own distinct responses to the surrounding attitude of censure, writers including Shakespeare, Donne, Milton, and Addison imagine death not as sin or sickness, but instead as a heroic gift, sexual release, elemental return, amorous fusion, or political self-rescue. “Joy of the worm” emerges here as an aesthetic mode that shades into schadenfreude, sadistic cruelty, and deliberate “trolling,” but can also underwrite powerful feelings of belonging, devotion, and love.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aEnglish literatureyEarly modern, 1500-1700xHistory and criticism. 0aSuicide in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  asuicide, Affect, pleasure, decorum, genre, tone, William Shakespeare, John Milton, Empedocles, Sigmund Freud.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022 Englishz978311099389908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022z9783110994810oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2022 Englishz978311099375208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2022z9783110993738oZDB-23-DKU08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076650940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226816517423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226816517/original  a978-3-11-076650-9  University of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  a978-3